@Bianca-T The reason you do not see any AD reads is that this variant is only called with samtools (MIP combines 3 callers: GATK, Freebayes and Samtools). Samtools uses another annotation DP4 to record the same information as the AD field. However, Scout does not read the DP4 field and hence will show AD=0,0 (we will have to think about the best way to fix that). Your variant has 9 high-quality non-reference bases (out of DP=54). 

@Bianca-T An aggregated genotype quality is calculated for all members and scored in the ranking model. An aggregated GT below 20 will add -5 to the rank score. 

@29vd Regarding family 15055. This is a multiallelic call C --> CG,CA that gets splitted. The C --> CG variant is very common and is filtered uppstream of Scout. There is very poor evidence for the C --> CA variant and it is only picked up by GATK, but with no solid support, hence AD=0,0 and "GT=./.". I am suprised GATK recorded it as a variant and it is very likely a false positive.

@kraigher, @suoto I keep coming back to what I think is the main user story to highlight "issues" for faster browsing of all VUnit output. If only 50% or so of those issues are found the solution for that story is severely flawed. A solution that will will find most issues and a few extra is also flawed but still much better. I think a rather simple set of keywords and maybe a few more complex tailored  for VUnit logging will take us far and a simple set for the simulator output will also be less vulnerable to changes between simulator releases.

Even if we start small just supporting VUnit logs the VHDL approach will run into problems when we decide to extend the support. Users and developers would have to deal with some coloring in the VHDL code and simulator coloring elsewhere.

I agree that generic coloring support doesn't fit well into the Python test runner either so why not have a separate Python module that wraps Colorama in the same way it wraps stdout (Colorama is actually not needed in Windows 10 which supports color codes natively)? Such a module will be imported/activated in the run script and it will be decoupled from the rest of VUnit

@JonathanHourany I'm sorry to hear you're having some difficulty with the naming of the parameters. 

unfortuanly I'm not going to change it. And I'll tell you why. :)

If you look at the Elasticsearch docs for the [Scroll API](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/search-request-scroll.html) you will see that `scroll` is used as the parameter for Elasticsearch. And as such I want to keep parity of the naming convention with Elasticsearch as well as the values for each parameter. 

```
POST /twitter/_search?scroll=1m
{
    "size": 100,
    "query": {
        "match" : {
            "title" : "elasticsearch"
        }
    }
}
```

Also the `scan` helper references itself as an abstraction around `elasticsearch.Elasticsearch.scroll` if we nav to the doc string for that function: https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/blob/52006f45620780046a0c7a2dfdf5777c3e4bfebc/elasticsearch/client/__init__.py#L993-L1001

You can see that it references the Elasticsearch Scroll API Documentation so that you can understand more about how the Scroll API works. 

This client is meant to be pretty thin. 

I hope this explanation helps.

@kmike Yes, I felt the same way. BTW, i think modifying the following part may also reduce memory use:

```
def sent2features(sent):
    return [word2features(sent, i) for i in range(len(sent))]

def sent2labels(sent):
    return [label for token, postag, label in sent]

def sent2tokens(sent):
    return [token for token, postag, label in sent]
```

to 

```
def sent2features(sent):
    return (word2features(sent, i) for i in range(len(sent)))

def sent2labels(sent):
    return (label for token, postag, label in sent)

def sent2tokens(sent):
    return (token for token, postag, label in sent)
```

It seems that the memory use didn't drop much, but the time consumption reduced.

