@aldanor The WIP implementation with the `throw` in `.ptr()` was my attempt to keep backwards compatibility, but it's pretty bad which is why I suggested banning `nullptr` and throwing early instead. It's a breaking change but it would help a lot (and not just for this issue). In the WIP implementation I had to add checks and `attribute_errors` in three places (+ the original skipped one). With the early error, that would go down to one (and no need to recreate Python error messages).

About the issues with lazy evaluation and proxy classes: actually the only real problem is with `auto` (this is the same one you pointed out in the other comment thread):
```c++
obj.attr("a") = 1;
auto b = obj.attr("a");
obj.attr("a") = 2;
b.cast<object>(); // expected 1, got 2
```
This is generally a problem with proxy classes and expression templates and `auto`. It was going to be addressed with `operator auto()` in C++17, but it got pushed back :(

I'm actually undecided if this is a major issue or just something to get used to (since it also affects some `std` library classes, like `std::vector<bool>`).

